stationary

Since we should always stabilize the variance first -> our only choice would be log first, then 1st diff

  • adf test: p<0.05, stationary
  • kpss test: p>0.05, stationary
variable_names <- c("import", "export", "cpi", "ppi", "bond", "sentiment", "USDX", "uncertainty")

pre covid

# Create an empty matrix to store the p-values and significance
test_pre <- matrix(NA, nrow = length(variable_names), 
                   ncol = 4)

# Perform ADF test for each variable's first-order difference
for (i in 1:length(variable_names)) {
  variable <- df_train1[[variable_names[i]]]
  variable_logdiff <- diff(log(variable))
  
  kpss_result_logdiff <- kpss.test(variable_logdiff)
  adf_result_logdiff <- adf.test(variable_logdiff, alternative = "stationary")
  
  adf_p_value <- adf_result_logdiff$p.value
  kpss_p_value <- kpss_result_logdiff$p.value
  
  adf_sig <- ifelse(adf_p_value < 0.05, "Stationary", "Not Stationary")
  kpss_sig <- ifelse(kpss_p_value > 0.05, "Stationary", "Not Stationary")
  
  test_pre[i, 1] <- adf_p_value
  test_pre[i, 2] <- adf_sig
  test_pre[i, 3] <- kpss_p_value
  test_pre[i, 4] <- kpss_sig
}

# Set the column names of the matrix
colnames(test_pre) <- c("adf.p.value", "adf.sig",
                        'kpss.p.value', 'kpss.sig')

# Set the row names of the matrix as the variable names
rownames(test_pre) <- variable_names

# Print the ADF test results for first-order differences
test_pre

Choose the same transformation method for all variables for better interpretability.

Granger Causality Test

Pre-Covid:

export + cpi + ppi

variables <- c("export", "cpi", "ppi", "bond", "sentiment", "USDX", "uncertainty")

# Initialize the result matrices
granger_pre <- matrix(NA, nrow = length(variables), ncol = 4)

# Iterate over variables and perform grangertest
for (i in 1:length(variables)) {
  
  var_to_result <- grangertest(train_pre[[variables[i]]], train_pre$import, order = 1)
  impt_to_result <- grangertest(train_pre$import, train_pre[[variables[i]]], order = 1)
  
  var.impt.p <- round(var_to_result$`Pr(>F)`[2], digits = 5)
  var.impt.sig <- ifelse(var.impt.p < 0.05, "Caused", "Not Caused")
  impt.var.p <- round(impt_to_result$`Pr(>F)`[2], digits = 5)
  impt.var.sig <- ifelse(impt.var.p < 0.05, "Caused", "Not Caused")
  
  granger_pre[i, 1] <- var.impt.p
  granger_pre[i, 2] <- var.impt.sig
  granger_pre[i, 3] <- impt.var.p
  granger_pre[i, 4] <- impt.var.sig
}

# Set column names
colnames(granger_pre) <- c("var.impt.p", "var.impt.sig",
                        "impt.var.p", "impt.var.sig")


# Create data frames with variables, p-values, and significance
granger_pre <- data.frame(variables, granger_pre)
granger_pre

VAR

pre-covid

pre.var <- cbind(ts(train_pre$import), 
                 ts(train_pre$export), 
                 ts(train_pre$ppi))
pre.var.optimal.p <- VARselect(pre.var, type= 'both',  season=12) # lag.max=max_lag,  season=12
pre.var.optimal.p$selection
## AIC(n)  HQ(n)  SC(n) FPE(n) 
##      2      2      2      2
var_logdiff <- matrix(NA, nrow = 4, ncol = 2)

for (p in 2:5) {
  var_model <- VAR(pre.var, p = p, type = "both", season = 12)
  var_model_srl_test <- serial.test(var_model, lags.pt = 24, type = "PT.asymptotic")
  
  p_value <- round(var_model_srl_test$serial$p.value, digits = 5)
  significance <- ifelse(p_value >= 0.05, "Not Autocorrelated", "Autocorrelated")
  var_logdiff[p-1, 1] <- p_value
  var_logdiff[p-1, 2] <- significance
}

colnames(var_logdiff) <- c("p-value", "significance")

var_logdiff
##      p-value   significance        
## [1,] "0.0969"  "Not Autocorrelated"
## [2,] "0.1252"  "Not Autocorrelated"
## [3,] "0.19486" "Not Autocorrelated"
## [4,] "0.22673" "Not Autocorrelated"

Forecast

dim(df_train1)
## [1] 204   9
dim(df_test1)
## [1] 12  9
lag_orders <- c(2, 3, 4, 5)
pre_result <- data.table()

for (lag in lag_orders) {
  var_logdiff <- VAR(pre.var, p = lag, type = "both", season = 12)
  
  forecast_data <- forecast(var_logdiff, h = 12)
  fcst_means <- forecast_data$forecast$ts.train_pre.import.$mean
  
  last_im <- log(df_train1$import[204])
  ori_result <- list()
  
  for (i in 1:12) {
    if (i <= 12) {
      last_im <- last_im + fcst_means[i]
    }
    ori_result[[i]] <- exp(last_im)
  }
  
  forecast_ts <- ts(unlist(ori_result))
  
  mae <- MAE(forecast_ts, ts(df_test1$import))
  mse <- MSE(forecast_ts, ts(df_test1$import))
  rmse <- RMSE(forecast_ts, ts(df_test1$import))
  mape <- MAPE(forecast_ts, ts(df_test1$import))
  
  aic <- AIC(var_logdiff)
  n <- length(pre.var)  # Number of observations
  k <- p + 1  # Correction term for AICc calculation
  aic_c <- aic + (2 * k * (k + 1)) / (n - k - 1)
  
  pre_result <- rbind(pre_result,
                      data.table(cbind("Pre-Covid", lag),
                                 MAE = mae, MSE = mse, RMSE = rmse, 
                                 AICc = aic_c, MAPE = mape))
}

print(pre_result) ## Select 5

plot(pre_impt_forecast)

# post-covid

plot(post_impt_forecast)

Impulse Response

Reference:

https://www.aptech.com/blog/the-intuition-behind-impulse-response-functions-and-forecast-error-variance-decomposition/

https://spureconomics.com/impulse-response-functions-after-var-and-vecm/

irf.int.pre <- irf(pre_var, response = "ts.train_pre.import.", n.ahead = 30, boot = TRUE)
plot(irf.int.pre)

Pre covid: * Export: converges to 0 pretty slowly; impact start with alternating sign (positive and negative alternating) * PPI: a short period of positive impact before periods 5; converges to 0 after period 10.

Post covid: * Export: converges to 0 even more slowly than pre-covid period, but has similar pattern. * PPI: same with export, PPI converges to 0 more slowly than pre-covid period. The 1st and 2nd spikes happen at period 2 and 5. This is likely a lagging response.

irf.int.post <- irf(post_var, response = "ts.train_post.import.", 
                    n.ahead = 30, boot = TRUE)
plot(irf.int.post)

Variance

For both the pre- and post-covid periods, more than 90% of the variation in the import is from shocks to the import itself.

For pre-covid, most of the remaining 10% is from ppi, while for post-covid, the remaining 10% is more equally splited by ppi and export.

plot(fevd(pre_var))

plot(fevd(post_var))
